{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9acbbcfe-9ca9-4f6b-a610-bd01155132d4","content":"Run:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThis uses the `~` (contains) operator to match any test whose fully qualified name includes `SmsNotificationTests`, which will run both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds` from that class.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"abf57800-a1fa-45b8-9651-c10259f3f121","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"TUnit uses its own test runner and has different filtering syntax than xUnit/NUnit with `dotnet test`. TUnit uses `--filter` but the filter syntax for class names works like this:\n\nFor TUnit, the standard `dotnet test --filter` works with fully qualified names. The class is `Contoso.Notifications.Tests.SmsNotificationTests`.\n\nThe command would be:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nOr you can use the class filter:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName=Contoso.Notifications.Tests.SmsNotificationTests\"\n\n\n```\n\nActually, I should simplify this—TUnit uses its own test adapter but still follows standard `dotnet test` filter expressions, so the straightforward approach is just to use the fully qualified name pattern matching.","outputTokens":287,"requestId":"0BDD:3D3F15:3BE83A:461C6F:69F00D58"},"id":"23fc6aec-3a36-476e-bf94-5baf5c90d1c8","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:29:03.593Z","parentId":"1a47ea40-0d86-4750-9d52-bcd93a505b1d"}
